Changelog
All notable changes to this project will be documented in this file. The format is based on Keep a Changelog.
[1.1] – 2026‑03‑08
Added
•	Release selection and file repair: The installer now automatically selects the correct OpenRelik release (default 0.7.0) from the upstream install.sh menu, rather than piping 1 blindly. It also validates and, if necessary, re‑downloads config.env and docker‑compose.yml using versioned filenames when the installer saves HTML error bodies.
•	Extra workers via override: Added support for the FLOSS, CAPA and LLM workers. These are installed via docker‑compose.override.yml alongside a local openrelik‑ollama service. After deployment you can pull an Ollama model (llama3) to enable the LLM worker.
•	Timesketch worker patch: The script now patches the existing openrelik‑worker‑timesketch service with correct Timesketch URL and credentials rather than specifying the entire service in the override.
•	Network integration persistence: The Timesketch override now makes the timesketch‑web container permanently join the openrelik_default network, so manual docker network connect is no longer needed after reboots.
•	Health checks and helper functions: Added helper functions (wait_for_healthy, wait_for_postgres, compose_up) and improved logging for container readiness and compose operations.
•	Deterministic startup scripts: The script writes /opt/timesketch/start.sh and /opt/openrelik/<compose‑dir>/start.sh that include overrides when starting the stacks.
Changed
•	Script name: The installer is now install_stack.sh instead of Install_Stack.sh for consistency.
•	Removed Hayabusa build step: The script no longer clones or builds openrelik‑worker‑hayabusa locally. OpenRelik release 0.7.0 includes the hayabusa worker by default, so building a local image is no longer necessary.
•	Improved readability: The README has been rewritten to explain why the installer exists, what it does, and how to use it. Sections about worker types and warnings have been clarified.
•	Cleaner cleanup: Removed the deletion of the hayabusa build directory; cleanup still removes all containers, volumes and custom networks. The warning about this destructive cleanup remains.
Fixed
•	Installer hangs on missing input: The upstream OpenRelik installer still prompts for version selection. Previously the script piped 1 which could break when releases change. The new version derives the correct menu option based on the desired release.
•	Invalid download fallback: When the upstream installer fails to download config.env or docker-compose.yml, the script now re‑downloads them using versioned filenames instead of unversioned names which 404.
[1.0] – Initial release
•	Initial version of the full‑stack installer combining Timesketch, OpenRelik and a locally built Hayabusa worker.
•	Set up network integration and Docker Compose overrides to add the Timesketch and Hayabusa workers.
•	Included destructive cleanup logic and health checks.
